            <p><note type="lingcomment">The language is archaic TB, but the ductus is rather an early classical form that lacks the characteristic shibbolets of the archaic script type. This text is an older version, the Berlin one <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht497"/> is younger, cf. also the use of the dual <hi>wi trauñc</hi> vs. plural <hi>wi traunta</hi>.</note><note type="parallels"><ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht497"/></note><note type="philcomment">This fragment is close to <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht497"/>, but not a direct parallel.</note><note type="remarks">A fragment from the middle of a leaf. Recto and verso side cannot be determined.</note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment">The reading and restoration <hi>pepä[kṣu]</hi> by Filliozat is impossible since the upper part of the akṣara is to high for a ka. Furthermore one does not expect a PPt at the beginning of a clause. In addition, a phrase <hi>pepärṣṣa witsäko</hi> recurs in <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-pkas9c"/> b3.</note><note corresp="#a5" type="philcomment">Pace Filliozat, one has to read <hi>paṇḍarokne</hi> for Skt. <hi>paṇḍuroga</hi>- 'jaundice, lit. yellow disease'.</note><note corresp="#a6" type="philcomment"><hi>dhanik</hi> is certainly a loan from Skt. <hi>dha/ānika</hi>- 'rich, opulent' rather than 'coriander' in the present context.</note><note corresp="#a7" type="philcomment"><hi>panāk</hi> is certainly a loan from Skt. <hi>pānaka</hi>- 'beverage, potion' (rather than Skt. <hi>panaka</hi>- 'arum lily', which is poisonous). In this case, we should have a perlative of manner.</note><note corresp="#b2" type="philcomment">One has to read <hi>tallentse</hi>, not <hi>tillentse</hi>, pace Filliozat. This forms calls to mind <hi>talle</hi>* 'burden, load'. One may surmise a pseudo-compound 'burden pertaining to blood'. It may be a calque of a Sanskrit compound.</note><note corresp="#b4" type="philcomment">Since a form <hi>tsämṣe</hi> gives no known word, one may surmise that the scribe omitted an akṣara, hence <hi>tsämṣe‹ñcai›</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b5" type="philcomment">One has to read <hi>śärttākru</hi>, a variant of <hi>śärtākru</hi> found in <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht497"/> b8. It is certainly a loan from Sanskrit that can be restored as <hi>śṛta-kuru-</hi> 'boiled rice'.</note><note corresp="#b8" type="philcomment">We expect a verbal form ending in <hi>ṣṣä〈ṃ〉</hi>. Unfortunately, it cannot be a form of <hi>pin</hi>- 'blow (into the nose)', because we would expect a subjunctive. A possibility is to restore <hi>(yänmā)ṣṣäṃ</hi> 'reaches', maybe as a cure involving inhalation.</note><note corresp="#b9" type="philcomment"><hi>ysā</hi> may be the start of a compound 'golden-x' or alternatively a noun with prefix <hi>yä(n)</hi>-.</note></p>
